inger a thank-you note that summed up how she felt about her progress in three words: “Reading is magic.”John Higgins: 206-464-3145 or jhiggins@seattletimes.com On Twitter @jhigginsST', '[{"tag":"problem","text":"In a nearby lab, Kuhl, one of the world\\’s leading experts on speech development, focuses on infants and toddlers — specifically how the connections in their brains change as they learn language. An adult brain has an estimated 86 billion neurons, which can each have as many as 1,000 to 10,000 connections with other neurons."}]', 'UW research on brain activity delivers lessons on how kids learn')
